Spotlight for now on TOB price and post- integration profitability improvement
Key: Historical Stock Performance Current Stock Price Price Target
Source: Refinitiv, Morgan Stanley Research

Our scenario calls for rising market expectations for drugstores and recognition of the firm's growth strategy leveraging M&A. Right now, we think the focus for Tsuruha will be on the tender offer price and post- integration growth story.
Source: Refinitiv, Morgan Stanley Research

Rising inbound demand and domestic consumer needs for drugs & cosmetics put overall industry growth at +10% and avg. P/E of 6 leading drugstore names (based on Bloomberg sets) back at the past- 5yr high of 26.4x.
Effects of various measures fuel higher growth than peers (F2/26 EPS 15% above our base case estimate).
Multiple fog Tsuruha is also 26.4x, on par with 6 drugstore avg.
Our base case assumes continued modest profit growth in real terms despite generally stiffer competition in the industry.
P/E of 20.8x applies the avg premium of +2.9% at which the stock has traded in the past 12 months vs. the avg. multiple for 6 leading drugstore names (20.2x based on recent Bloomberg forecasts).

Industry growth slows as stiffer competition reignites price competition, and rising costs also contribute to lowering avg. P/E of the 6 major drugstore names to the past- 5yr floor of 15.7x (Bloomberg sets).
We also assume F2/26 EPS falls 20% short of the base case given a tough business environment.
P/E is 16.2x, based on the avg premium of +2.9% to the 6 major drugstore name average above (same as the base case).

Equal- weight (E). The stock's total return is expected to be in line with the average total return of the analyst's industry (or industry team's) coverage universe, on a risk- adjusted basis, over the next 12- 18 months.

Not- Rated (NR). Currently the analyst does not have adequate conviction about the stock's total return relative to the average total return of the analyst's industry (or industry team's) coverage universe, on a risk- adjusted basis, over the next 12- 18 months.

Underweight (U). The stock's total return is expected to be below the average total return of the analyst's industry (or industry team's) coverage universe, on a risk- adjusted basis, over the next 12- 18 months.
